13. Diffie-Hellman Weakness — MITM Attack

Problem
	•	Diffie-Hellman does NOT verify identity
	•	No guarantee Alice ↔ Bob directly

⸻

Attack Flow (Mallory)

1. Alice sends A → Mallory intercepts  
2. Mallory sends M to Bob (pretends to be Alice)  
3. Bob sends B → Mallory intercepts  
4. Mallory sends M to Alice (pretends to be Bob)


⸻

Result

Alice ↔ Mallory ↔ Bob

	•	Alice computes key with Mallory
	•	Bob computes key with Mallory
	•	Mallory has BOTH keys

✔ Can:
	•	Read messages
	•	Modify messages

⸻

14. Why MITM Happens

No authentication in Diffie-Hellman
→ Cannot verify identity of other party


⸻

15. Solution — PKI (Public Key Infrastructure)

Purpose
	•	Verify identity of communicating parties
	•	Prevent MITM attacks

⸻

16. How PKI Solves the Problem

Key Idea

Trusted third party (CA) signs certificates


⸻

Certificate Contains
	•	Public key
	•	Domain name
	•	CA signature

⸻

Verification Process

1. Server sends certificate  
2. Browser checks CA signature  
3. Uses CA public key  
4. Confirms certificate is valid  

✔ If trusted → continue
❌ If not → warning/block

⸻

17. Real Example (HTTPS)
	•	When visiting a website:
	•	Browser shows 🔒 (lock icon)
	•	Means:

Valid certificate + encrypted connection


⸻

18. Certificate Authority (CA)

Examples:
	•	DigiCert
	•	Let’s Encrypt

⸻

Role

CA signs certificate → proves identity of server


⸻

19. Certificate Signing Process

Step 1 — Generate CSR

openssl req -new -nodes -newkey rsa:4096 -keyout key.pem -out cert.csr


⸻

What happens here
	•	Generate:
	•	Private key
	•	Public key
	•	Create CSR (request for certificate)

⸻

Step 2 — Send to CA
	•	CA verifies identity
	•	Signs certificate

⸻

Step 3 — Use Signed Certificate
	•	Install on server
	•	Used for HTTPS

⸻

20. TLS + PKI + Diffie-Hellman (Combined Flow)

1. Client connects to server  
2. Server sends certificate  
3. Client verifies using CA  
4. Secure identity confirmed  
5. Diffie-Hellman used → generate session key  
6. Symmetric encryption used for communication


⸻

21. Key Takeaways
	•	Diffie-Hellman alone ❌ vulnerable to MITM
	•	PKI adds:
	•	Identity verification
	•	Trust
	•	HTTPS = combination of:
	•	PKI + TLS + symmetric encryption

⸻

22. One-line Summary

Diffie-Hellman enables key exchange but is vulnerable to MITM; PKI and certificates solve this by verifying identities and enabling secure HTTPS communication.